                  <handDesc>
                     <summary>Nos. 1-7 (<locus>fols. 1-169</locus>): Sephardic-Italian semi-cursive script; No. 8 (<locus>fols. 170r-194r</locus>): Italian cursive and semi-cursive script; Nos. 9-10 (<locus>fols. 195r-202r</locus>): Sephardic-Italian semi-cursive (<locus>fols. 195-197</locus>) and Italian cursive scripts; Nos. 11 (<locus>fols. 203r-246r</locus>): Italian cursive script; Nos. 12-13 (<locus>fols. 247-272</locus>): Sephardic semi-cursive script; No. 14 (<locus>fols. 273-276</locus>): Italian (semi-)cursive script</summary>
                     <handNote>Nos. 1-7: <locus>fols. 17-26</locus> by another hand, <locus>fols. 161-169</locus> in Italian script, <locus>fols. 101-104 and 160</locus> in a rather Ashkenazic script.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>

               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate>Nos. 1-7 (<locus>fols. 1-169</locus>): [c. 1755-75 (<locus>fols. 1r, 16v, and 160r</locus>)]; No. 8 (<locus>fols. 170r-194r</locus>): [c. 1600 (watermarks: Briquet no. 13960, dated 1594-9)]; Nos. 9-10 (<locus>fols. 195r-202r</locus>): [c. 1730]; Nos. 11 (<locus>fols. 203r-246r</locus>): [c. 1730]; Nos. 12-13 (<locus>fols. 247-272</locus>): [early 15th cent. (watermarks similar to Briquet no. 3527, dated 1412-39)]; No. 14 (<locus>fols. 273-276</locus>): [18th cent.]</origDate>
                     <origPlace>Nos. 1-7 (<locus>fols. 1-169</locus>): Venice; No. 8 (<locus>fols. 170r-194r</locus>): [Italy]; Nos. 9-10 (<locus>fols. 195r-202r</locus>): [Padua]; Nos. 11 (<locus>fols. 203r-246r</locus>): [Padua]; Nos. 12-13 (<locus>fols. 247-272</locus>): [Spain or Provence]; No. 14 (<locus>fols. 273-276</locus>): [Italy]</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>It belonged to Rabbi Isaac Samuel Reggio's (1784-1855) library, which was purchased en bloc by the Bodleian Library in 1853.</acquisition>
